                <head>No. 95.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hunter</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Beach</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1885-02-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">February</hi> 28, 1885</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 24.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to your dispatch No. 23 in relation to
                    the imprisonment of Mr. J. R. Santos at Manta, I have to inform you that
                    Congress has requested the President to use his efforts to secure a speedy and
                    fair trial and to protect the life and property of the prisoner. The Department
                    has replied that the recourse of rebutting evidence of his intention of not
                    returning to the United States, &amp;c., is still open to Mr. Santos, and his
                    right thereto will be insisted upon.</p>
                <p>You will demand and make every endeavor to secure for Mr. Santos the right of the
                    treaty, especially in the matter of rebutting evidence to show that he retained
                    by intention and act his acquired United States citizenship.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WM. HUNTER,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Second Assistant Secretary.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
